metadata.name: ZOOM (4hwf) #13
metadata.description:
"Das System lässt keine Überraschung zu. Überraschung ist Ausdruck partieller Unkenntnis. Überraschung weist auf Mangel von Wissen hin, deutet Leerstellen an. Bisher hatten sie keine Leerstellen festgestellt." — Herbert W. Franke

ZOOM explores linear scaling of pixels by zooming into a noisy framebuffer. Various zoom levels are composed one below the other, becoming a cinematic animation through iteration of the hue values of the pixels in the framebuffer.

In Gedenken an Herbert W. Franke
Kim Asendorf, 2022

metadata.name: Mines #33
metadata.description:
"He found himself wondering at times, especially in the autumn, about the wild lands, and strange visions of mountains that he had never seen came into his dreams"
- J.R.R. Tolkien

Mines is an exploration of these mountains of dreams, and the ancient mechanics that shape them. The work of eons, where the landscapes we know rise and fall like ocean waves.

To know them, we must go beneath the mountain.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press “s” to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at specific width
- Use param ?bg=true to render on full color background (instead of the default dark background)

metadata.name: Oxygen #84
metadata.description:
Oxygen makes strange forms of life thrive even in the darkest of places.

This is a generative piece using curated randomness to create textures, generate distortion fields, simulate growth and create compositions.

The work is best viewed in high resolution, but due to the time it takes to render, the preview image is capped to only 1000 pixels in height. You can change the resolution by pressing keys

- 'm' for medium  (height=2000px)
- 'l' for large (height=3500px)
- 'x' for extra large (height=5000px) 

outputs. 

Press 's' to save the output as a PNG file.

For even larger outputs, you can open the work in live mode and append the text '?size=10000' to the URL. Here, you can change the number (10000) to the desired height in pixels. 

Please note, that a very high-resolution image may take a very long time to render and some browsers are not able to save the image. However, even a 10000 pixels tall outputs have been generated during testing.

metadata.name: Sketch Book #42
metadata.description:
Sketch Book is a generative collection that imagines an abstract sketch built with lines and shapes in harmony with each other.

It’s called Sketch Book as it started with me sketching a bunch of lines in p5.js and then warping them to give them a natural waviness. The artwork combines subdivision and domain warping techniques before drawing the final lines and shapes on the canvas. 

Sketch Book renders as a fixed resolution output (1000x1200px). Controls (in live view): 

Press [2] to render at 2000x2400px
Press [4] to render at 4000x4800px
Press [8] to render at 8000x9600px
Press [s] to save the current view (default or higher resolution image)

metadata.name: Kyoshin #6
metadata.description:
Kyoshin(虚心) means to be free from all bias, like frankness and open mindedness.

metadata.name: Primordial #113
metadata.description:
Primordial is a study of abstract forms. The algorithm, written in p5.js and WebGL, utilizes domain warping to create twisted fields of color and then overlays thousands of tiny lines to provide depth and texture. The outputs are chaotic but not completely formless, like a swirling mass of plasma from the early universe, or a strange proto-life form suspended in prehistoric ooze.

CONTROLS:

1-9: Increase resolution and save image in PNG format

B: Toggle borders on/off

F: Fullscreen
P: Portrait
L: Landscape
S: Square

For third party license information, please see license.md

David Brice Allen
October 2022

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #452
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: "make a robot face" #41
metadata.description:
"make a robot face"

While experimenting with character creation using code written by GPT-3, I grew a strong love for these minimal, friendly, and blocky faces that the AI created after it was tasked to make a robot face. With further prompting I then used gpt3 to create more attributes and features based off the original robot face code.

This project is a generative art experiment using a Text2Code workflow. The JavaScript code for this project was written entirely by AI using GPT-3. None of the code was altered or created by a human aside from changing Math.random() with fxrand().

Project CoDexter by @BrainArtLabs
